TITLE: Using Custom Columns in Drift Queries
DESCRIPTION: Demonstrates how to include custom expressions as columns in a SELECT query, including computed values such as LIKE operators and concatenated strings.
SOURCE: https://github.com/simolus3/drift/blob/develop/docs/docs/dart_api/select.md#2025-04-17_snippet_9

LANGUAGE: dart
CODE:
```
// calculates both the content length (for all rows), and whether the content matches
// a filter (dynamic for each filter)
Future<List<ResultRow>> contentInfo(String filter) {
  // We'll need to define what columns to read at this point. The first argument
  // is a list of columns for which the runtime can determine the type. In this
  // case, that's the content of each todo entry. The second argument contains
  // expressions whose type can't be determined at runtime. For those expressions,
  // we need to tell drift about the expected type.
  final contentLength = todos.content.length.cast<int>();
  final matches = todos.content.like('%$filter%').cast<bool>();
  final query = select(
    columns: [todos.content],
    variables: {
      // give it a friendly name for later. If you don't add a name, drift will
      // generate one for you.
      'length': contentLength,
      'matches': matches,
    },
    from: todos,
  );

  // .then() will run for each row, a bit like .map but more type safe
  return query.then((row) {
      final content = row.read(todos.content);
      final length = row.read<int>('length');
      final rowMatches = row.read<bool>('matches');
      return CustomResult(content, length, rowMatches);
  }).get();
}
```

